# Agent workflow

This repository is set up for model-neutral, docs-driven collaboration. `AGENTS.md` is the entry point only; durable guidance lives here and elsewhere under `docs/`.

## Where information belongs

### Durable docs

Use `docs/` for information that should survive beyond the current task:

- architecture and component boundaries
- domain rules and glossary
- coding, testing, and workflow standards
- runbooks
- stable findings worth preserving

Use [AGENTS.md](../AGENTS.md) as the map of what already exists before creating a new durable file.

### Issues and PRs
{% if platform == 'github' %}

Issues and PRs on GitHub are the authoritative record of all planned and completed work.

**Issues** capture problems, goals, and planning. Run `gh issue list` at the start of a session to orient on open work. When you discover a bug, open an issue before or alongside the fix — do not silently fix things with no record.

**PRs** carry the implementation. Always reference the issue: `Fixes #N` or `Part of #N`. PR body explains what changed, why, and how to verify. **PRs are reviewed and merged by the human — do not auto-merge.**

```bash
gh issue list
gh issue create --title "..." --body "..."
gh pr create --title "..." --body "..." --base main
gh pr list
gh release create v1.2.3 --title "v1.2.3" --notes "..."
```
{% else %}

Issues and PRs on Forgejo are the authoritative record of all planned and completed work.
{% if platform == 'both' %}
GitHub is a convenience mirror — code is readable there, but all workflow (issues, PRs, releases) happens on Forgejo.
{% endif %}

**Issues** capture problems, goals, and planning. Run `fj issue list` at the start of a session to orient on open work. When you discover a bug, open an issue before or alongside the fix — do not silently fix things with no record.

**PRs** carry the implementation. Always reference the issue: `Fixes #N` or `Part of #N`. PR body explains what changed, why, and how to verify. **PRs are reviewed and merged by the human — do not auto-merge.**

```bash
fj issue list
fj issue create --title "..." --body "..."
fj pr create --title "..." --body "..." --base main
fj pr list
fj release create v1.2.3 --title "v1.2.3" --notes "..."
```
{% endif %}

**Issue title conventions:**
- Plain English, problem-focused. Describes what is wrong or needed, not what will be done.
- No type prefix (`fix:`, `docs:` etc. belong on commits, not issue titles).
- Do not preempt the solution in the title.

### Working memory

`.ai/` is gitignored. Use it for session handoffs, scratch notes, ad-hoc scripts, and intermediate outputs. Anything worth preserving beyond the session belongs in an issue comment or in `docs/`.

## Branching

```
<type>/<short-description>
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `refactor`, `chore`, `test`

Always branch from `main`. Keep branches short-lived.

## Drift policy

If a change affects durable behaviour, update the relevant doc in the same change. Do not turn task chatter into durable docs — move only stable conclusions into `docs/`.

When a session produces a durable finding, route it to the right existing file without creating a new one. Create a new `docs/domain/` file only when a genuinely new subject area has no home. Write an ADR (in `docs/adr/`) whenever a non-obvious architectural decision is made.

## Recommended session flow

1. Read `AGENTS.md`.
2. Check `.ai/` for session notes or handoff context from the previous session.
3. Run `{% if platform == 'github' %}gh{% else %}fj{% endif %} issue list` to orient on open work.
4. Read only the durable docs relevant to the task.
5. Make the smallest coherent change that moves the task forward.
6. Update docs if durable behaviour changed.
7. Did this session make any non-obvious design decisions? If yes, write an ADR in `docs/adr/` before handing off.
8. Commit; leave a brief handoff note in `.ai/` before pausing or switching models.

## Handoff expectations

- What changed and what is next.
- Assumptions made and open questions.
- Whether any ADRs were written or a decision was deferred (and why).
- Suggested commit message or confirmation the branch is clean.

## Releases

Triggered by a version tag:

```bash
git tag v1.2.3
git push origin v1.2.3
```

This triggers the CD workflow{% if has_api %} which builds and pushes the Docker image{% endif %}. Use [semver](https://semver.org/): `vMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`.
